      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Understanding Premium Squares: DL, TL, DW, TW Strategy Guide</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-12">June 12, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>5 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Premium squares are what transform Scrabble from a simple vocabulary exercise into a spatial strategy game. The difference between a good player and a great one often comes down to how they use — and deny — these coloured squares. This guide explains each type, where they sit on the board, and how to build your strategy around them.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Four Types of Premium Squares</h2>
      <p>The Scrabble board has 61 premium squares arranged in a symmetrical pattern. Each type serves a different purpose:</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Double Letter Score (DL) — Light Blue</h3>
      <p>There are 24 DL squares on the board. When you place a tile on a DL square, that single tile's point value is doubled. The rest of the word scores normally.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> Placing a Z (10 points) on a DL square scores 20 points for that tile alone. A humble D (2 points) on DL only becomes 4 — still useful but not game-changing.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategy:</strong> DL squares matter most with high-value tiles. Placing an E (1 point) on DL gains you only 1 extra point. Placing a J (8 points) on DL gains you 8 extra. Always aim to put your most valuable tile on the DL when possible.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Triple Letter Score (TL) — Dark Blue</h3>
      <p>There are 12 TL squares, making them rarer than DL squares. A tile on TL has its value tripled.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> An X (8 points) on TL scores 24 points for that tile. A Q (10 points) on TL scores 30 points — often more than entire words without premium squares.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategy:</strong> TL squares are prime real estate for J, X, Q, and Z tiles. A single tile on TL can outscore an opponent's entire turn. When you draw a high-value tile, immediately look for TL opportunities before considering other plays.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Double Word Score (DW) — Pink</h3>
      <p>There are 16 DW squares (plus the centre star, which also acts as DW on the first turn). After calculating the full word score (including any letter multipliers), the entire total is doubled.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> A word scoring 15 points that covers a DW square becomes 30 points. If the word also has a letter on DL, you apply the DL first, then double the entire sum.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategy:</strong> DW squares reward longer words because every tile in the word benefits from the doubling. A 7-letter word on DW could score 40+ points before even considering bingo bonuses. The centre star on the first turn means every opening word is automatically doubled — make it count.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-200 mt-6 mb-3">Triple Word Score (TW) — Red</h3>
      <p>There are only 8 TW squares, positioned in the corners and midpoints of the board edges. The entire word score is tripled after all letter multipliers are applied.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> A word scoring 20 points that passes through a TW becomes 60 points. Combined with a high-value tile on a TL elsewhere in the same word, scores can reach 80-100+ points in a single turn.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategy:</strong> TW squares are the most powerful spaces on the board. Competitive players plan multiple turns ahead to access them. Equally important: don't give your opponent easy access to TW squares by placing tiles adjacent to them without using them yourself.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Board Layout: Where Premium Squares Sit</h2>
      <p>The board is perfectly symmetrical — mirrored across both the horizontal and vertical centre lines. This means premium squares appear in predictable positions:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TW squares:</strong> Four corners (A1, A8, A15, H1, H15, O1, O8, O15) — actually positioned at corners and mid-edges</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>DW squares:</strong> Diagonal lines radiating from the centre, plus the centre star</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TL squares:</strong> Scattered in an inner ring and outer ring pattern</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>DL squares:</strong> The most common premium, distributed across the middle and inner zones</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Knowing these positions from memory gives you a planning advantage. You can look at your rack and immediately think "I have a Z — where's the nearest TL I can reach?"</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The One-Turn Rule</h2>
      <p>A crucial rule that many casual players get wrong: <strong>premium squares only activate once</strong>. They apply only on the turn a tile is first placed on them. Once covered, the square is "used up." Any future words that pass through that tile score the tile at its face value with no multiplier.</p>
      <p>This means you need to use premium squares when you first reach them — there are no second chances. It also means that once a TW square is covered, it's no longer a threat. Experienced players sometimes deliberately cover dangerous premium squares with low-scoring plays to deny them to opponents.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Stacking Multipliers</h2>
      <p>One of the most powerful scoring techniques involves activating multiple premium squares in a single play:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TL + DW:</strong> A high-value letter gets tripled, then the whole word gets doubled. This creates explosive scores.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>DW + DW:</strong> If your word spans two DW squares (possible with longer words), the word is doubled twice — effectively ×4.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TW + TW:</strong> The legendary double-triple. If you span two TW squares (only possible with a 15-letter word or by extending across the board), the word is tripled twice — ×9. This is the single highest multiplier possible.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>DL/TL + TW:</strong> Apply the letter multiplier first, then triple the entire word total. A Z on TL in a TW word: Z scores 30, then the whole word triples.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Defensive Strategy: Denying Premium Squares</h2>
      <p>Scoring isn't just about maximising your own points — it's about minimising your opponent's opportunities. Key defensive principles:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't feed TW squares:</strong> Placing a tile adjacent to an uncovered TW gives your opponent a pathway to triple their next word. Only play near TW if you're using it yourself.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Block with low-value words:</strong> If an opponent is clearly heading for a TW, consider playing a short word that covers or blocks the approach.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Keep the board tight:</strong> Compact boards with fewer open lines give opponents fewer premium square opportunities. Spread boards benefit the player with better tiles.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Sacrifice points for safety:</strong> Sometimes a 15-point safe play is better than a 25-point play that opens a TW for your opponent to score 50+.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Centre Star</h2>
      <p>The centre square (marked with a star ★) functions as a DW square on the first turn only. This means the first player's word is automatically doubled. Smart first players maximise this by playing their highest-scoring word possible as an opener.</p>
      <p>After the first turn, the centre star has no further effect. It's just another regular square.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Putting It All Together</h2>
      <p>Premium squares are what give Scrabble its strategic depth. Without them, the game would be purely about vocabulary — whoever knows the longest, rarest words wins every time. With premium squares, a player who knows fewer words but positions them brilliantly can outperform a walking dictionary.</p>
      <p>Use our <a href="/" class="text-blue-400 hover:underline">free word finder</a> to discover words from your tiles in realtime, then decide which ones give you the best premium square access. The tool shows instant scores for every match — no signup, no limits, completely free. Combine that information with board awareness, and you'll be scoring at a whole new level.</p>

